hard link vs soft link

hard link: A hard link is an additional name for an existing file. When you create a hard link, you aren't creating a shortcut; 
you are creating a second "door" to the exact same room.
- both original file and hard link share same inode number (check by use ls -i)
- if delete the original file, the hard link still works and data still in the disk
- can't link to directories abd can't span acros different system (partitions)

soft link: A symlink is more like a Windows shortcut. It is a special file that contains a text path to another file or directory
- has its own unique inode number
- if delete the original file, symlink becomes broken or 'dangling' 'cause path no longer exist
- can link between directories and can point on different file systems or even acroos a network
